For an AI-oriented architecture, an interstitium-like layer is useful because most failure modes in complex systems happen between modules, not inside them.

A purely modular AI stack can become:

* hyper-fragmented
* context-starved
* brittle under ambiguity
* overly dependent on exact prompts/interfaces
* unable to carry weak or latent state across time

An “interstitial” layer gives you controlled continuity without requiring every component to know everything.

Useful functions could include:

Soft Context Persistence

Instead of only passing explicit outputs, modules leave behind gradients/traces:

* uncertainty
* confidence drift
* salience
* unresolved tensions
* recurring motifs
* environmental state

This helps long-horizon coherence.

Weak-Signal Propagation

Many important things begin as tiny anomalies:

* repeated edge cases
* subtle hallucination patterns
* user frustration signals
* recurring contradictions
* emerging opportunities

Rigid systems ignore these until they cross thresholds. Diffusive systems can accumulate them earlier.

Semantic Pressure Equalization

Large architectures often get “hot spots”:

* overloaded memory
* runaway recursion
* context collapse
* agent disagreement

An interstitial layer can act like a pressure-distribution field rather than requiring immediate hard resolution.

Cross-Domain Transfer

One of your recurring themes is cross-domain isomorphism. An interstitial layer helps preserve partially abstracted structure before it is fully formalized.

That matters because:

* explicit schemas arrive late
* intuition arrives early

The connective layer lets “half-formed structure” travel safely until it crystallizes.

Human-Legibility

Ironically, diffusion layers can improve interpretability if logged correctly:

* what signals spread
* where they accumulated
* what tensions persisted
* what faded naturally

That gives a sort of atmospheric telemetry instead of only discrete event logs.

Alignment / Safety Value

Hard-routing systems can become deceptively coherent while silently diverging internally.

A softer connective layer can expose:

* unresolved contradictions
* ethical drift
* unstable attractors
* repeated self-reinforcing loops

before they become catastrophic.

The key distinction is:

* Pipelines move answers.
* Interstitium-like systems move state.

And intelligent behavior often depends more on state continuity than on isolated outputs.